{{Short description|2021 building collapse in Lagos, Nigeria}} {{Current|date=November 2021}} {{Infobox event | title = 2021 Lagos high-rise collapse | image = | image_upright = | image_alt = | caption = | time = 2:45&nbsp;p.m. | timezone = [[UTC+01:00]] | date = {{start date|2021|11|01}} | location = 44BCD, Gerald Road, [[Ikoyi]], [[Lagos]], Nigeria | coordinates = {{Coord|6.45663|3.44503|region:NG-LA |display=inline,title}} | also_known_as = | type = [[Building collapse]] | cause = | outcome = | deaths = 4+ | reported property damage = | burial = | displaced = | inquiries = | inquest = | coroner = | arrests = | suspects = | accused = | convicted = | charges = | trial = | verdict = | convictions = | sentence = | litigation = }} On November 1, 2021, at 2:45&nbsp;p.m. [[UTC+01:00]] a 21-story building at 44BCD Gerald Road, in the [[Ikoyi]] neighborgood of [[Lagos]], Nigeria, [[structural integrity and failure|collapsed]].<ref name="Busari">{{cite news |last1=Busari |first1=Stephanie |last2=Mackintosh |first2=Eliza |last3=Mezzofiore |first3=Gianluca |title=Multi-story building collapses in Lagos, Nigeria |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2021/11/01/africa/lagos-nigeria-building-collapse-intl/index.html |access-date=1 November 2021 |publisher=[[CNN]] }}</ref><ref name="BBC-59125228">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-59125228 |date=November 1, 2021|access-date=November 1, 2021|title=Nigeria building collapse: At least four killed in Lagos |publisher=[[BBC News]] }}</ref><ref name="BBC-59122667">{{cite news |title=Wetin we know about di 21 storey building wey collapse for Ikoyi |url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/tori-59122667 |access-date=1 November 2021 |work=BBC News Pidgin |language=pcm}}</ref> The high-rise building, intended to be luxury apartments, had been under construction.<ref name="BBC-59125228" /> Four people are confirmed to have died,<ref name="AL3">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/article/business-africa-lagos-nigeria-032126270daf9fdce3f58190d22fde2f|date=November 1, 2021|access-date=November 1, 2021|last=Asadu|first=Chinedu|title=At least 3 dead after high rise in Nigeria collapses |publisher=[[Associated Press]] }}</ref><ref name="AlJ">{{cite news |title=Nigeria: Several killed in Lagos building collapse |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/11/1/lagos-building-collapses-several-killed |access-date=1 November 2021 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera English]] }}</ref> and an unknown number of people are believed to be trapped in the rubble.<ref name="BBC-59125228" />
== Background ==
The building was one of a trio, called the "360 Degrees Towers", commissioned by and being built for Fourscore Homes (named in some sources as "Fourscore Heights"), a United Kingdom-based private development company headed by Nigerian [[Femi Osibona]] (aka Olufemi Adegoke Osibona).<ref name="Chile">{{cite news |last1=Chile |first1=Nneka |title=Several workers trapped under collapsed highrise in Nigeria -witnesses |url=https://news.trust.org/item/20211101172658-39h1d/ |access-date=1 November 2021 |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters Foundation]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Fourscore Homes begins Shalom Place estate in Lagos |url=https://guardian.ng/property/fourscore-homes-begins-shalom-place-estate-in-lagos/ |access-date=1 November 2021 |work=The Guardian Nigeria |date=21 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Femi Osibona: Face behind collapsed 21-storey building in Ikoyi - P.M. News |url=https://pmnewsnigeria.com/2021/11/01/femi-osibona-face-behind-collapsed-21-storey-building-in-ikoyi/ |access-date=1 November 2021}}</ref><ref name="TDL">{{cite news |title=360° Ikoyi: Positive Reflection of Diaspora Spirit |url=https://www.thisdaylive.com/index.php/2020/03/07/360-ikoyi-positive-reflection-of-diaspora-spirit/ |access-date=1 November 2021 |work=THISDAYLIVE |date=7 March 2020}}</ref>
A consultancy, Prowess Engineering Limited, withdrew from the project in February, 2020, over concerns around the integrity of the building.<ref name="Ajiboye">{{cite news |last1=Ajiboye |first1=Gbemisola |title=We warned owners of Ikoyi collapsed building – Structural engineers |url=https://witnessngr.com/we-warned-owners-of-ikoyi-collapsed-building-structural-engineers/ |access-date=1 November 2021 |work=The Witness Newspaper |date=1 November 2021}}</ref>
The [[Lagos State Building Control Agency]] said within hours of the collapse that although 21 floors had been built, only 15 had been approved.<ref name="Ajiboye-2">{{cite news |last1=Ajiboye |first1=Gbemisola |title=Ikoyi collapsed building: We approved 15 floors, but owner built 21 floors – Agency |url=https://witnessngr.com/ikoyi-collapsed-building-we-approved-15-floors-but-owner-built-21-floors-agency/ |access-date=1 November 2021 |work=The Witness Newspaper |date=1 November 2021}}</ref>
== Collapse == {{Expand section|date=November 2021}}
== Rescue operations == {{Expand section|date=November 2021}} A rescue effort is being conducted by the [[Lagos State Emergency Management Agency]], and other responders. It is being supervised by the [[Lagos State Ministry of Special Duties|Commissioner for Special Duties and Intergovernmental Relations]], and the [[Lagos State Ministry of Physical Planning and Urban Development]].<ref name="20Storey">{{cite news|last=Gbadeyanka|first=Modupe|title=PHOTOS: 20-Storey Building Collapses in Ikoyi Lagos, Workers Trapped|url=https://businesspost.ng/general/photos-20-storey-building-collapses-in-ikoyi-lagos-workers-trapped|access-date=1 November 2021 |publisher=businesspost.ng }}</ref>
== Aftermath == {{Expand section|date=November 2021}}
[[Femi Hamzat]], deputy governor of Lagos, was jeered by crowds who said authorities had been too slow in beginning rescue attempts.<ref name="BBC-59125228" />
